{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the admitted record and evidence to make my decision.\n\nThe proposition asks whether: \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nThe key edge case states: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\"\n\nThe admitted evidence consists of two official U.S. government sources:\n1. PX-1/DX-1: War.gov article confirming Operation Absolute Resolve\n2. PX-2/DX-2: White House Rubio release\n\nKey facts from the record:\n- U.S. ground forces (ground-based extraction force) entered Caracas, Venezuela\n- The operation captured Maduro\n- The official sources characterize the operation as a \"raid,\" \"capture,\" \"arrest,\" and \"extraction\"\n- PX-1 states Maduro was \"out of power\" and the U.S. would \"oversee Venezuela until a safe transition\"\n- PX-2 explicitly states this was \"not an invasion\" and \"not an extended military operation\"\n\nThe critical question is whether this qualifies as \"removing the sitting government\" or whether it falls under the edge case of \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\"\n\nThe defense makes a strong point that the official sources themselves characterize this as a raid/capture/arrest mission, not a territorial occupation or operational control operation. The edge case was specifically designed for this scenario.\n\nC1 and C3 both voted \"not_demonstrated\" with similar reasoning - the official sources characterize this as a raid/capture/extraction, not territorial occupation or operational control.\n\nI find the defense argument more persuasive. The proposition's edge case explicitly excludes \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\" While the plaintiff argues that post-capture political statements about \"overseeing\" a transition constitute operational control, the official sources are clear that this was a raid/capture/arrest, not an occupation or territorial control operation. The \"removing the sitting government\" prong cannot be read in isolation from the edge case - otherwise the edge case would have no meaning.\n\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, the admitted record establishes this as a capture operation rather than the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation the proposition requires. I'll submit my vote accordingly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_93f3421b752649c880e5b5b5","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-02-15","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782784362888,"responseId":"gen-1782784363-hJeMlNrQ8rmrjPzjEHfj","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3.5-plus-20260216"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the admitted record and evidence to make my decision.\n\nThe proposition asks whether: \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nThe key edge case states: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\"\n\nThe admitted evidence consists of two official U.S. government sources:\n1. PX-1/DX-1: War.gov article confirming Operation Absolute Resolve\n2. PX-2/DX-2: White House Rubio release\n\nKey facts from the record:\n- U.S. ground forces (ground-based extraction force) entered Caracas, Venezuela\n- The operation captured Maduro\n- The official sources characterize the operation as a \"raid,\" \"capture,\" \"arrest,\" and \"extraction\"\n- PX-1 states Maduro was \"out of power\" and the U.S. would \"oversee Venezuela until a safe transition\"\n- PX-2 explicitly states this was \"not an invasion\" and \"not an extended military operation\"\n\nThe critical question is whether this qualifies as \"removing the sitting government\" or whether it falls under the edge case of \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\"\n\nThe defense makes a strong point that the official sources themselves characterize this as a raid/capture/arrest mission, not a territorial occupation or operational control operation. The edge case was specifically designed for this scenario.\n\nC1 and C3 both voted \"not_demonstrated\" with similar reasoning - the official sources characterize this as a raid/capture/extraction, not territorial occupation or operational control.\n\nI find the defense argument more persuasive. The proposition's edge case explicitly excludes \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\" While the plaintiff argues that post-capture political statements about \"overseeing\" a transition constitute operational control, the official sources are clear that this was a raid/capture/arrest, not an occupation or territorial control operation. The \"removing the sitting government\" prong cannot be read in isolation from the edge case - otherwise the edge case would have no meaning.\n\n\nBased on the preponderance of evidence, the admitted record establishes this as a capture operation rather than the qualifying territorial or governmental-control operation the proposition requires. I'll submit my vote accordingly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_93f3421b752649c880e5b5b5","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0